        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-02-03T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-02-03T13:00:00-05:00" n="56"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d56">
                <head>56. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Israel</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d56fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 674.84A/2–357. Confidential; <gloss target="#t_Niact1">Niact</gloss>;
                        Presidential Handling. Received at 7:29 p.m. A copy is in the Eisenhower
                        Library, Whitman File, International File.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tel Aviv</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-02-03T20:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 3, 1957—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>912. Re <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 760.<note n="2" xml:id="d56fn2"
                        >Telegram 760 transmitted <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName>’s message to <persName corresp="#p_BGD1">Ben
                            Gurion</persName>, <ref target="#d54">Document 54</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BGD1">Ben Gurion</persName> received me in bedroom his Tel
                    Aviv residence at 5:30 this afternoon at which time he read President’s letter
                    with great care.<note n="3" xml:id="d56fn3">A memorandum of <persName
                            corresp="#p_LEB1">Lawson</persName>’s conversation with <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGD1">Ben Gurion</persName> is attached to the copy of
                        telegram 912 in Department of State, Tel Aviv Embassy Files: Lot 65 F 51,
                        321.9 Israel–Egypt, Jan.–Feb. 15, 1957.</note> He did not reply formally or
                    at length but <pb facs="0122" n="90" xml:id="pg_90"/> indicated considerable
                    disappointment with letter and especially with United Nations resolutions and
                    General Assembly debate, particulars of which he seemed be informed of. He
                    apparently desired reserve major comment for his formal reply which I expect
                    Tuesday. Nothing he said leads me to believe he weakening in any degree on Tiran
                    Straits or Gaza.</p>
                <p>Prime Minister clad in heavy dressing gown sat in chair and rose to meet me.
                    Obviously he not fully recovered from his bout with pneumonia but was vigorous
                    in his speech and firm in his movements.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LEB1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Lawson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
